18 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
19 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
20 Article – Natural Resources
21 3–501.
22 (a) In this subtitle the following words have the meanings indicated.
23 (b) “Biodiversity” means the full range of living organisms native to a region.
24 (c) “Irreplaceable natural area” means an area with habitat necessary to support:
25 (1) A unique natural community; or
26 (2) A plant or animal species listed as threatened or endangered under
27 Title 10, Subtitle 2A of this article.
28 (d) “Program” means the Irreplaceable Natural Areas Program.
29 (e) “Unique natural community” means an area that:
30 (1) Has an assemblage of native plants or animals that is rare or declining
31 in the State; or
32 (2) Supports an unusually pristine example of a native ecosystem type.

SENATE BILL 431 3
1 3–502.
2 (a) There is an Irreplaceable Natural Areas Program in the Department.
3 (b) The purpose of the Program is to preserve Maryland’s native biodiversity on
4 State–owned land managed by the Department for current and future residents of the
5 State.
6 3–503.
7 (A) On or before July 1, 2023, the Department shall adopt regulations to carry out
8 this subtitle, including regulations:
9 (1) Designating irreplaceable natural areas on State–owned land managed
10 by the Department; and
11 (2) Establishing management objectives for irreplaceable natural areas,
12 including:
13 (i) A map depicting boundaries for each area;
14 (ii) A description of the unique features and threats for each area;
15 and
16 (iii) Compatible and incompatible activities for each area.
17 (B) ON OR BEFORE JULY 1, 2033, AND AT LEAST EVERY 10 YEARS
18 THEREAFTER, THE SECRETARY SHALL REVIEW AND, IF WARRANTED, UPDATE THE
19 REGULATIONS REQUIRED UNDER THIS SECTION.
20 4–2A–01.
21 (a) In this subtitle the following words have the meanings indicated.
22 (F–1) “FORESEEABLE FUTURE” MEANS AS FAR INTO THE FUTURE AS THE
23 DEPARTMENT CAN MAKE REASONABLY RELIABLE PREDICTIONS, ON A
24 CASE–BY–CASE BASIS, ABOUT THE THREATS TO A SPECIES OF FISH AND THE
25 SPECIES’ RESPONSE TO THOSE THREATS:
26 (1) USING THE BEST AVAILABLE DATA; AND
27 (2) TAKING INTO ACCOUNT CONSIDERATIONS INCLUDING:
28 (I) THE SPECIES’ LIFE–HISTORY CHARACTERISTICS;

4 SENATE BILL 431
1 (II) THE PROJECTED TIME FRAME OF THE THREAT; AND
2 (III) ENVIRONMENTAL VARIABILITY.
3 (F–2) (1) “HARM” MEANS AN ACT THAT KILLS OR INJURES ANY SPECIES OF
4 FISH.
5 (2) “HARM” INCLUDES AN ACT THAT SIGNIFICANTLY MODIFIES OR
6 DEGRADES A HABITAT, THEREBY KILLING OR INJURING ANY SPECIES OF FISH BY
7 SIGNIFICANTLY IMPAIRING ESSENTIAL BEHAVIORAL PATTERNS, INCLUDING
8 BREEDING, FEEDING, AND SHELTERING.
9 (i) “Take” means to harass, harm, pursue, hunt, shoot, wound, kill, trap, capture,
10 or collect, or to attempt to engage in any such conduct.
11 (j) “Threatened species” means any species of fish which appears likely, within
12 the foreseeable future, to become endangered, including any species of fish determined to
13 be a “threatened species” pursuant to the Endangered Species Act.
14 4–2A–04.
15 (a) Any species of fish determined to be an endangered species pursuant to the
16 Endangered Species Act shall be deemed to be an endangered species under the provisions
17 of this subtitle and any species of fish determined to be a threatened species pursuant to
18 the Endangered Species Act shall be deemed to be a threatened species under the provisions
19 of this subtitle. The Secretary may determine, in accordance with this section, that any
20 threatened species is an endangered species throughout all or any portion of the range of
21 the species within the State.
22 (b) In addition to the species deemed to be endangered or threatened pursuant to
23 the Endangered Species Act, the Secretary, by rule or regulation, shall determine whether
24 any species of fish normally occurring within the State is an endangered or threatened
25 species due to any of the following factors:
26 (1) The present or threatened destruction, modification, or curtailment of
27 its habitat or range;
28 (2) Overutilization for commercial, sporting, scientific, educational, or
29 other purposes;
30 (3) Disease or predation;
31 (4) The inadequacy of existing regulatory mechanisms; or

SENATE BILL 431 5
1 (5) Other natural or manmade factors affecting its continued existence
2 within the State.
3 (c) (1) The Secretary shall make determinations required by subsection (b) of
4 this section [on]:
5 (I) ON the basis of the best scientific, commercial, and other data
6 available and after consultation, as appropriate, with federal agencies, other interested
7 State agencies, other states having a common interest in the species, and interested persons
8 and organizations; AND
9 (II) WITHOUT REFERENCE TO POSSIBLE ECONOMIC OR OTHER
10 IMPACTS OF SUCH DETERMINATION.
11 (2) In determining whether any species of fish is an endangered species or
12 a threatened species, the Secretary shall take into consideration any actions being carried
13 out or about to be carried out by the federal government, other states, other agencies of this
14 State, or political subdivisions, or by any other person, which may affect the species under
15 consideration.
16 (d) Except with respect to species of fish determined to be endangered or
17 threatened species under the provisions of subsection (a) of this section, the Secretary may
18 not add a species to nor remove a species from any list published unless he first:
19 (1) Publishes a public notice of the proposed action;
20 (2) Furnishes notice of the proposed action to the Governor of any state
21 sharing a common border with this State and in which the subject species is known to exist;
22 and
23 (3) Allows at least 30 days following publication for comment from the
24 public and other interested parties.
25 (e) Notwithstanding the provisions of subsection (d) of this section, if the
26 Department determines that an emergency situation exists involving the continued
27 existence of the species as a viable component of the State’s fish population it may add the
28 species to the lists if it publishes a public notice that an emergency situation exists together
29 with a summary of facts which support this determination.
30 (f) THE SECRETARY SHALL DELIST A SPECIES IF THE SECRETARY
31 DETERMINES, BASED ON CONSIDERATION OF THE FACTORS AND STANDARDS SET
32 FORTH IN SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION, THAT THE BEST SCIENTIFIC AND
33 COMMERCIAL DATA AVAILABLE SUBSTANTIATE THAT:
34 (1) THE SPECIES IS EXTINCT;

